UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1309
1 AN ACT relating to educators.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. KRS 161.028 is amended to read as follows:
4 (1) The Education Professional Standards Board is recognized to be a public body
5 corporate and politic and an agency and instrumentality of the Commonwealth, in
6 the performance of essential governmental functions. The Education Professional
7 Standards Board has the authority and responsibility to:
8 (a) Establish standards and requirements for obtaining and maintaining a teaching
9 certificate;
10 (b) 1. Set standards for, approve, and evaluate college, university, and school
11 district programs for the preparation of teachers and other professional
12 school personnel. The standards set for college or university programs
13 for the preparation of teachers and other professional school
14 personnel shall:
15 a. Not require achieving a minimum composite or component score
16 on any assessment, including but not limited to a summative
17 assessment, as a:
18 i. Condition of admission to a program;
19 ii. Barrier to enrollment, continuation, or progression within
20 a program; or
21 iii. Requirement for clinical placement, student-teaching, or
22 other field-based experience;
23 b. Require an applicant for an undergraduate initial certification
24 program to complete and submit:
25 i. At the time of initial application, verification that the
26 candidate has completed a formative basic skills assessment
27 selected by the Education Professional Standards Board
Page 1 of 12
BR130900.100 - 1309 - XXXX 1/29/2026 2:18 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1309
1 and required by the college or university; and
2 ii. After an applicant has been admitted but prior to the first
3 day of attendance, the results of the formative basic skills
4 assessment taken in accordance with subpart i. of this
5 subdivision, which shall be used by the college or university
6 solely as a formative diagnostic assessment to determine
7 areas where a candidate may require academic support,
8 remediation, or supplemental instruction; and
9 c. Require program policy, for a candidate that is required to
10 complete a formative basic skills assessment selected by the
11 Education Professional Standards Board pursuant to subdivision
12 b. of this subparagraph, that:
13 i. Ensures that a candidate completes assessment prior to
14 initial application;
15 ii. Ensures that a candidate for an undergraduate initial
16 certification program submits the results of the assessment
17 prior to the first day of attendance; and
18 iii. Provides academic supports for a candidate aligned with
19 the candidate's performance on the formative basic skills
20 assessment.
21 Nothing in this subparagraph shall be interpreted to prohibit the
22 board or an education preparation program provider from considering
23 assessment results, in combination with other relevant indicators, to
24 determine candidate readiness for in-program milestones after a
25 candidate has enrolled.
26 2. College or university programs may be approved by the board for a
27 college or university with regional institutional level accreditation or
Page 2 of 12
BR130900.100 - 1309 - XXXX 1/29/2026 2:18 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1309
1 national institutional level accreditation that is recognized by the United
2 States Department of Education and is eligible to receive federal funding
3 under 20 U.S.C. secs. 1061 to 1063. Program standards shall reflect
4 national standards and shall address, at a minimum, the following:
5 a.[1.] The alignment of programs with the state's core content for
6 assessment as defined in KRS 158.6457;
7 b.[2.] Research-based classroom practices, including effective classroom
8 management techniques;
9 c.[3.] Emphasis on subject matter competency of teacher education
10 students;
11 d.[4.] Methodologies to meet diverse educational needs of all students;
12 e.[5.] The consistency and quality of classroom and field experiences,
13 including early practicums and student teaching experiences;
14 f.[6.] The amount of college-wide or university-wide involvement and
15 support during the preparation as well as the induction of new
16 teachers;
17 g.[7.] The diversity of faculty;
18 h.[8.] The effectiveness of partnerships with local school districts; and
19 i.[9.] The performance of graduates on various measures as determined
20 by the board;
21 (c) Conduct an annual review of diversity in teacher preparation programs;
22 (d) Provide assistance to universities and colleges in addressing diversity, which
23 may include researching successful strategies and disseminating the
24 information, encouraging the development of nontraditional avenues of
25 recruitment and providing incentives, waiving administrative regulations
26 when needed, and other assistance as deemed necessary;
27 (e) Discontinue approval of programs that do not meet standards or whose
Page 3 of 12
BR130900.100 - 1309 - XXXX 1/29/2026 2:18 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1309
1 graduates do not perform according to criteria set by the board;
2 (f) Issue, renew, revoke, suspend, or refuse to issue or renew; impose
3 probationary or supervisory conditions upon; issue a written reprimand or
4 admonishment; or any combination of actions regarding any certificate;
5 (g) Develop specific guidelines to follow upon receipt of an allegation of sexual
6 misconduct by an employee certified by the Education Professional Standards
7 Board. The guidelines shall include investigation, inquiry, and hearing
8 procedures which ensure the process does not revictimize the alleged victim
9 or cause harm if an employee is falsely accused;
10 (h) Receive, along with investigators hired by the Education Professional
11 Standards Board, training on the dynamics of sexual misconduct of
12 professionals, including the nature of this abuse of authority, characteristics of
13 the offender, the impact on the victim, the possibility and the impact of false
14 accusations, investigative procedures in sex offense cases, and effective
15 intervention with victims and offenders;
16 (i) Recommend to the Kentucky Board of Education the essential data elements
17 relating to teacher preparation and certification, teacher supply and demand,
18 teacher attrition, teacher diversity, and employment trends to be included in a
19 state comprehensive data and information system and periodically report data
20 to the appropriate Interim Joint Committee on Education;
21 (j) Submit reports to the Governor and the Legislative Research Commission and
22 inform the public on the status of teaching in Kentucky;
23 (k) Devise a credentialing system that provides alternative routes to gaining
24 certification and greater flexibility in staffing local schools while maintaining
25 standards for teacher competence;
26 (l) Develop a professional code of ethics;
27 (m) Charge reasonable fees for the issuance, reissuance, and renewal of
Page 4 of 12
BR130900.100 - 1309 - XXXX 1/29/2026 2:18 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1309
1 certificates that are established by administrative regulation. The proceeds
2 shall be used to meet a portion of the costs of the issuance, reissuance, and
3 renewal of certificates, and the costs associated with disciplinary action
4 against a certificate holder under KRS 161.120;
5 (n) Waive a requirement that may be established in an administrative regulation
6 promulgated by the board. A request for a waiver shall be submitted to the
7 board, in writing, by an applicant for certification, a postsecondary institution,
8 or a superintendent of a local school district, with appropriate justification for
9 the waiver. The board may approve the request if the person or institution
10 seeking the waiver has demonstrated extraordinary circumstances justifying
11 the waiver. Any waiver granted under this subsection shall be subject to
12 revocation if the person or institution falsifies information or subsequently
13 fails to meet the intent of the waiver;
14 (o) Promote the development of one (1) or more innovative, nontraditional or
15 alternative administrator or teacher preparation programs through public or
16 private colleges or universities, private contractors, the Department of
17 Education, or the Kentucky Commonwealth Virtual University and waive
18 administrative regulations if needed in order to implement the program;
19 (p) Grant approval, if appropriate, of a university's request for an alternative
20 program that enrolls an administrator candidate in a postbaccalaureate
21 administrator preparation program concurrently with employment as an
22 assistant principal, principal, assistant superintendent, or superintendent in a
23 local school district. An administrator candidate in the alternative program
24 shall be granted a temporary provisional certificate and shall be a candidate in
25 the Kentucky Principal Internship Program, notwithstanding provisions of
26 KRS 161.030, or the Superintendent's Assessment process, notwithstanding
27 provisions of KRS 156.111, as appropriate. The temporary certificate shall be
Page 5 of 12
BR130900.100 - 1309 - XXXX 1/29/2026 2:18 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1309
1 valid for a maximum of two (2) years, and shall be contingent upon the
2 candidate's continued enrollment in the preparation program and compliance
3 with all requirements established by the board. A professional certificate shall
4 be issued upon the candidate's successful completion of the program,
5 internship requirements, and assessments as required by the board;
6 (q) Employ consultants as needed;
7 (r) Enter into contracts. Disbursements to professional educators who receive less
8 than one thousand dollars ($1,000) in compensation per fiscal year from the
9 board for serving on an assessment validation panel or as a test scorer or
10 proctor shall not be subject to KRS 45A.690 to 45A.725;
11 (s) Sponsor studies, conduct research, conduct conferences, and publish
12 information as appropriate; and
13 (t) Issue orders as necessary in any administrative action before the board.
14 (2) (a) The board shall be composed of seventeen (17) members. The secretary of the
15 Education and Labor Cabinet and the president of the Council on
16 Postsecondary Education, or their designees, shall serve as ex officio voting
17 members. The Governor shall make the following fifteen (15) appointments:
18 1. Nine (9) members who shall be teachers representative of elementary,
19 middle or junior high, secondary, special education, and secondary
20 vocational classrooms;
21 2. Two (2) members who shall be school administrators, one (1) of whom
22 shall be a school principal;
23 3. One (1) member representative of local boards of education; and
24 4. Three (3) members representative of postsecondary institutions, two (2)
25 of whom shall be deans of colleges of education at public universities
26 and one (1) of whom shall be the chief academic officer or head of an
27 educator preparation program of an independent not-for-profit college or
Page 6 of 12
BR130900.100 - 1309 - XXXX 1/29/2026 2:18 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1309
1 university.
2 (b) The members appointed by the Governor shall be confirmed by the Senate
3 under KRS 11.160. If the General Assembly is not in session at the time of the
4 appointment, persons appointed shall serve prior to confirmation, but the
5 Governor shall seek the consent of the Senate at the next regular session or at
6 an intervening extraordinary session if the matter is included in the call of the
7 General Assembly.
8 (c) Each appointed member shall serve a three (3) year term. A vacancy on the
9 board shall be filled in the same manner as the original appointment within
10 sixty (60) days after it occurs. A member shall continue to serve until his or
11 her successor is named. Any member who, through change of employment
12 status or residence, or for other reasons, no longer meets the criteria for the
13 position to which he or she was appointed shall no longer be eligible to serve
14 in that position.
15 (d) Members of the board shall serve without compensation but shall be permitted
16 to attend board meetings and perform other board business without loss of
17 income or other benefits.
18 (e) A state agency or any political subdivision of the state, including a school
19 district, required to hire a substitute for a member of the board who is absent
20 from the member's place of employment while performing board business
21 shall be reimbursed by the board for the actual amount of any costs incurred.
22 (f) A chairman shall be elected by and from the membership. A member shall be
23 eligible to serve no more than three (3) one (1) year terms in succession as
24 chairman. Regular meetings shall be held at least semiannually on call of the
25 chairman.
26 (g) The commissioner of education shall serve as executive secretary to the board
27 and may designate staff to facilitate his or her duties.
